00:52:04.496 --> 00:52:07.420
Prof: Well I don't know
about that.

00:52:07.420 --> 00:52:13.414
The question is really a
perplexity about what I have

00:52:13.414 --> 00:52:15.030
been saying.
 

00:52:15.030 --> 00:52:21.159
In Inferno, will is crucial and
you are absolutely right.

00:52:21.159 --> 00:52:26.809
There cannot be a sin unless
there is a will involved.

00:52:26.809 --> 00:52:29.659
In Purgatorio,
the argument here seems to be--

00:52:29.659 --> 00:52:32.525
the way I have been following
it from Cantos XV,

00:52:32.525 --> 00:52:35.940
XVI, XVII and the way it's
going to be developed in XVIII

00:52:35.940 --> 00:52:39.690
and actually frankly XIX,
where Dante goes on telling a

00:52:39.690 --> 00:52:43.867
dream--
Dante makes the word of love

00:52:43.867 --> 00:52:49.469
the crucial act of our being in
the word,

00:52:49.469 --> 00:52:53.159
relating us to God,
we are related to God,

00:52:53.159 --> 00:52:55.429
really born through the way of
love,

00:52:55.429 --> 00:52:59.067
therefore, the way of the heart
and not unnecessarily through

00:52:59.067 --> 00:53:01.250
some abstract metaphysical
issues.

00:53:01.250 --> 00:53:06.760
Then the issue becomes how is
this love related to the will?

00:53:06.760 --> 00:53:09.219
Is Dante being uncertain
between the two?

00:53:09.219 --> 00:53:13.952
What is the moral--Dante begins
in Canto XV talking about moral

00:53:13.952 --> 00:53:17.204
responsibilities,
this kind of free subjection

00:53:17.204 --> 00:53:20.166
that we have,
and an inner light that is

00:53:20.166 --> 00:53:21.500
available to us.
 

00:53:21.500 --> 00:53:26.679
Then he--Canto XVI we'll also
talk about the--

00:53:26.679 --> 00:53:29.539
in Canto XVI he talks about
creation,

00:53:29.539 --> 00:53:33.097
the creation of the soul,
the freedom with which God

00:53:33.097 --> 00:53:35.960
creates and that freedom
authorizes us.

00:53:35.960 --> 00:53:41.030
It becomes a sort of ground for
the human freedom.

00:53:41.030 --> 00:53:43.119
Then in XVII,
first of all,

00:53:43.119 --> 00:53:47.943
he talks about an imagination
which is completely free of any

00:53:47.943 --> 00:53:53.489
contact with the world and then
talks about this theory of love,

00:53:53.489 --> 00:53:57.173
that rational love that
organizes, the love of knowledge

00:53:57.173 --> 00:53:59.050
that organizes everything.
 

00:53:59.050 --> 00:54:01.960
I could just have stopped there
and shown you,

00:54:01.960 --> 00:54:06.192
this is really what the text
says, and maybe ask you to

00:54:06.192 --> 00:54:10.815
connect imagination and love
that I read at the two sides of

00:54:10.815 --> 00:54:14.731
Canto XVII,
at the very center of the poem,

00:54:14.731 --> 00:54:19.369
almost to imply that we can
love only and so far as--

00:54:19.369 --> 00:54:23.219
and we can love as well as our
imagination takes us to loving.

00:54:23.219 --> 00:54:26.500
That's clearly one of the
images.

00:54:26.500 --> 00:54:29.590
But clearly there is more in
that debate.

00:54:29.590 --> 00:54:33.677
The debate is that if I love
according well,

00:54:33.677 --> 00:54:36.150
or not enough,
or too much,

00:54:36.150 --> 00:54:41.190
that has to do with the way I
perceive the world.

00:54:41.190 --> 00:54:46.224
Why does he have to talk about
an imagination which is so

00:54:46.224 --> 00:54:50.268
unbounded that it needs nothing
of reality?

00:54:50.268 --> 00:54:53.226
I mean to say this that in the
subject and I call it--I say

00:54:53.226 --> 00:54:55.929
well this is a visionary aspect
of the imagination.

00:54:55.929 --> 00:54:59.610
It's a poet who thinks of
himself as being the visionary

00:54:59.610 --> 00:55:00.079
poet.
 

00:55:00.079 --> 00:55:03.489
You have an idea of Romantic
poets,

00:55:03.489 --> 00:55:06.514
for instance,
English Romantic poets who

00:55:06.514 --> 00:55:10.469
distinguish between fantasy and
the imagination,

00:55:10.469 --> 00:55:14.521
though Dante does it in terms
of this imaginative power that

00:55:14.521 --> 00:55:17.199
removes me from the world of
reality.

00:55:17.199 --> 00:55:21.684
It takes me away and opens up
new spaces and the mind in

00:55:21.684 --> 00:55:22.420
itself.
 

00:55:22.420 --> 00:55:25.567
I ask this question though from
another point of view,

00:55:25.567 --> 00:55:29.250
which I think is connected to
what we have been saying here.

00:55:29.250 --> 00:55:33.416
Can Dante ever write this kind
of poem by being bound to the

00:55:33.416 --> 00:55:37.443
world of reality and to the way
in which the real world is

00:55:37.443 --> 00:55:38.150
known?
 

00:55:38.150 --> 00:55:39.840
Clearly the answer is no.
 

00:55:39.840 --> 00:55:44.686
The only way that Dante can
come to God and the vision of

00:55:44.686 --> 00:55:47.889
God is by agreeing with this
idea,

00:55:47.889 --> 00:55:51.351
yielding, surrendering to the
power of the imagination that

00:55:51.351 --> 00:55:53.619
will take him out of the real
world.

00:55:53.619 --> 00:55:57.635
You cannot really write a poem
like the Divine Comedy by

00:55:57.635 --> 00:56:02.204
following rules and laws,
whether they are rhetorical,

00:56:02.204 --> 00:56:06.730
or whether they are just pure
ideas of style.

00:56:06.730 --> 00:56:11.423
You try to--you have to go on
imagining things that don't

00:56:11.423 --> 00:56:15.030
really--are available to our
perceptions.

00:56:15.030 --> 00:56:16.639
That, to me,
is the issue,

00:56:16.639 --> 00:56:19.409
that's how I have been moving
this issue.

00:56:19.409 --> 00:56:23.025
I think that the poem,
that Dante's voice is suspended

00:56:23.025 --> 00:56:26.639
between these two possibilities
of the imagination.

00:56:26.639 --> 00:56:29.619
An imagination that has to
accept the world of reality,

00:56:29.619 --> 00:56:33.335
an ordinary imagination,
and yet there is also another

00:56:33.335 --> 00:56:37.768
idea of the imagination,
which is so much more powerful.

00:56:37.768 --> 00:56:40.661
But, if we accept this as being
true for the poem,

00:56:40.661 --> 00:56:43.965
it follows we have to ask the
question of, what about the

00:56:43.965 --> 00:56:44.849
moral life?
 

00:56:44.849 --> 00:56:49.250
Is the moral life then one that
where Dante's saying,

00:56:49.250 --> 00:56:53.943
that in effect,
all the language of blame and

00:56:53.943 --> 00:56:58.438
praise,
which depends on accepting

00:56:58.438 --> 00:57:03.449
limits and free subjection to
rules,

00:57:03.449 --> 00:57:06.280
is that--is he saying that that
is also--

00:57:06.280 --> 00:57:08.420
maybe it's arbitrary?
 

00:57:08.420 --> 00:57:11.329
That there may be some other
law that he has to discover?

00:57:11.329 --> 00:57:14.503
I don't think that there is yet
an answer here,

00:57:14.503 --> 00:57:18.159
but that's the problem that I
was trying to convey.

00:57:18.159 --> 00:57:22.326
Does that answer
your--provisionally--your

00:57:22.326 --> 00:57:24.460
perplexities,
okay.

00:57:28.409 --> 00:57:29.159
Yes.
 

00:57:29.159 --> 00:57:32.682
Student:
