He asks that question,
does this visionary power come

01:00:15.670 --> 01:00:19.307
to me from the outside,
or is it something that is

01:00:19.307 --> 01:00:21.090
within human beings?
 

01:00:21.090 --> 01:00:23.768
That's the question.
 

01:00:23.768 --> 01:00:26.789
He doesn't answer that question
at that point.

01:00:26.789 --> 01:00:31.108
What he does say is,
well this is the image that

01:00:31.108 --> 01:00:36.161
came to me, the image of a
martyr who committed suicide,

01:00:36.161 --> 01:00:39.929
and he goes on with his three
images.

01:00:39.929 --> 01:00:45.271
He doesn't answer that directly
and I think that he wants to

01:00:45.271 --> 01:00:50.250
keep you guessing if this is a
human transgression or an

01:00:50.250 --> 01:00:53.510
acknowledgement of human limits.
 

01:00:53.510 --> 01:00:58.052
He--I don't think that he knows
yet, at this point,

01:00:58.052 --> 01:01:02.139
what the unfolding of that
dilemma will be.

01:01:02.139 --> 01:01:06.594
He wants us to think in terms
of that dilemma and that dilemma

01:01:06.594 --> 01:01:08.860
is at the heart of Purgatory.
 

01:01:08.860 --> 01:01:13.469
The dilemma between what is
this power?

01:01:13.469 --> 01:01:17.257
I have a power within me
that--without which I can never

01:01:17.257 --> 01:01:20.079
really go to God,
and is this in any way a

01:01:20.079 --> 01:01:21.320
transgression?
 

01:01:21.320 --> 01:01:25.518
Do I need a transgression in
order to come to God?

01:01:25.518 --> 01:01:29.733
Ulysses thought that there
would be no knowledge without

01:01:29.733 --> 01:01:30.960
transgression.
 

01:01:30.960 --> 01:01:34.599
Maybe Adam in the Garden also
thought that there would be no

01:01:34.599 --> 01:01:37.376
knowledge without
transgression--that the real

01:01:37.376 --> 01:01:39.289
knowledge is to transgress.
 

01:01:39.289 --> 01:01:42.000
Is Dante thinking that way?
 

01:01:42.000 --> 01:01:46.144
Or maybe he's thinking that
there is no transgression

01:01:46.144 --> 01:01:50.610
without, at the same time,
a sense of the limitations.

01:01:50.610 --> 01:01:53.181
That indeed,
that the idea of transgression

01:01:53.181 --> 01:01:55.570
depends on some sense of
limitations.

01:01:55.570 --> 01:01:56.969
Do you see what I'm saying?
 

01:01:56.969 --> 01:02:00.851
What the argument seems to me
could very well be,

01:02:00.851 --> 01:02:04.733
that in effect pride and
humility are really more

01:02:04.733 --> 01:02:08.050
connected than what we like to
think.

01:02:08.050 --> 01:02:14.070
We are always proud and Dante
would say, it's good.

01:02:14.070 --> 01:02:17.920
To me that's what Canto X,
XI, and XII were saying.

01:02:17.920 --> 01:02:20.952
You may not agree with that
reading, that pride is good in

01:02:20.952 --> 01:02:24.519
the measure in which I can reach
out for something really higher.

01:02:24.519 --> 01:02:26.018
That's not bad.
 

01:02:26.018 --> 01:02:30.219
What is bad is that that blinds
me to something else.

01:02:30.219 --> 01:02:34.400
I take that to be Franciscan
thinking.

01:02:34.400 --> 01:02:39.398
He is invoking the humblest
voice of the whole literary

01:02:39.398 --> 01:02:43.842
tradition up to this time,
the Canticle of all

01:02:43.842 --> 01:02:45.510
Creatures.
 

01:02:45.510 --> 01:02:50.166
I'm glad that you are giving me
the opportunity to refocus on

01:02:50.166 --> 01:02:54.202
the fact that that dilemma
between pride and humility

01:02:54.202 --> 01:02:58.548
reappears as a question of
limits and transgressions with

01:02:58.548 --> 01:03:02.429
the imagination and knowledge
and with love.

01:03:02.429 --> 01:03:07.744
Of course, Dante would say that
there is such a thing of love

01:03:07.744 --> 01:03:11.152
within--
with laws and yet love is one

01:03:11.152 --> 01:03:16.197
of those experiences where we
usually don't like to believe

01:03:16.197 --> 01:03:19.590
that there are limits,
right?

01:03:19.590 --> 01:03:25.139
You don't want anybody to
come--I hope--to come to your

01:03:25.139 --> 01:03:29.663
door and say,
I love you in a very reasonable

01:03:29.663 --> 01:03:33.570
way and with a lot of
limitations.

01:03:33.570 --> 01:03:40.119
I'm sure you'll give--kick him
out.

01:03:40.119 --> 01:03:44.478
Love is one of those
experiences exactly like the

01:03:44.478 --> 01:03:47.824
imagination,
that the powers of which seem

01:03:47.824 --> 01:03:51.519
always to be transgressing
whatever limitations we want

01:03:51.519 --> 01:03:53.817
to--
we wanted to transgress the

01:03:53.817 --> 01:03:57.000
limitations,
rationally, reasonably we want

01:03:57.000 --> 01:03:58.268
to impose on it.
 

01:03:58.268 --> 01:04:00.429
This is the question that Dante
is raising.

01:04:00.429 --> 01:04:05.010
You cannot have,
I think that you are--

01:04:05.010 --> 01:04:07.150
you are onto the right track
with your--

01:04:07.150 --> 01:04:10.443
in your paraphrasing the
whole--in your asking the

01:04:10.443 --> 01:04:13.670
question that maybe
transgression and limitations

01:04:13.670 --> 01:04:16.090
really have to be seen together.
 

01:04:16.090 --> 01:04:18.349
Pride and humility will have to
be seen together;

01:04:18.349 --> 01:04:21.219
subjection and freedom will
have to be seen together.

01:04:21.219 --> 01:04:26.619
They are not terms which are so
far apart from each other.

01:04:26.619 --> 01:04:31.592
Each involves the other,
that's why I call it a paradox,

01:04:31.592 --> 01:04:35.300
the knot that joins these
things together,

01:04:35.300 --> 01:04:37.110
is exactly that.
 

01:04:37.110 --> 01:04:41.130
Is this--am I--did I confuse
all of you today here?

01:04:41.130 --> 01:04:44.349
Oh my, then I will confuse you
next time.

01:04:44.349 --> 01:04:46.590
Other questions that we have?
 

01:04:48.949 --> 01:04:49.599
Yes.
 

01:04:49.599 --> 01:04:53.489
Student:
Can you talk about the section

01:04:53.489 --> 01:04:58.851
in Canto XV where he's talking
about how true love and the love

01:04:58.851 --> 01:05:00.925
of God is like a mirror?
 

01:05:00.925 --> 01:05:02.829
It's around line 70...
 

01:05:02.829 --> 01:05:05.250
Prof: Canto XV.
 

01:05:05.250 --> 01:05:07.300
Student:
Line 75...

01:05:07.300 --> 01:05:08.860
Prof: Yes.
 

01:05:08.860 --> 01:05:11.652
Student:
How love of God is like his

01:05:11.652 --> 01:05:14.443
mirror that--the more people
that love God,

01:05:14.443 --> 01:05:18.432
the more love he gives back and
it's like a mirror that keeps

01:05:18.432 --> 01:05:20.492
reflecting and amplifying love.
 

01:05:20.492 --> 01:05:24.150
And I was wondering--I was
intrigued by the image of the

01:05:24.150 --> 01:05:28.204
mirror, so I was hoping that you
could talk a little bit about

01:05:28.204 --> 01:05:32.260
how the image of the mirrors and
the idea of mirrors maybe are

01:05:32.260 --> 01:05:34.387
part of Dante's way of thinking.
 

01:05:34.387 --> 01:05:37.047
Prof: The--this is
around line 75,

01:05:37.047 --> 01:05:38.510
right?
 

01:05:38.510 --> 01:05:41.719
Let me just read this whole
paragraph.

01:05:41.719 --> 01:05:48.635
Dante is in the--describing the
virtue that is opposed to envy,

01:05:48.635 --> 01:05:55.105
mercy, the idea of--the notion
of mercy and because--I read

01:05:55.105 --> 01:05:59.539
from 65 on:
"Because thou still

01:05:59.539 --> 01:06:05.945
settest thy mind on earthly
things, thou gatherest darkness

01:06:05.945 --> 01:06:09.150
from the very light."
 

01:06:09.150 --> 01:06:15.208
That's part of--sort of
reversals that we--how light

01:06:15.208 --> 01:06:20.579
induces and generates darkness;
it's a certain kind of light.

01:06:20.579 --> 01:06:25.056
We seem to believe or to think
in terms of the light that is

01:06:25.056 --> 01:06:28.472
available to us,
but that does not necessarily

01:06:28.472 --> 01:06:32.719
produce more light,
but can dim our understanding

01:06:32.719 --> 01:06:35.929
about the way things really are.
 

01:06:35.929 --> 01:06:40.159
"That infinite and
unspeakable good which is there

01:06:40.159 --> 01:06:44.780
above speeds to love as a
sunbeam comes to a bright body;

01:06:44.780 --> 01:06:48.030
so much it gives of itself as
it finds ardor,

01:06:48.030 --> 01:06:52.396
so the more charity extends the
more does the eternal goodness

01:06:52.396 --> 01:06:55.702
increase upon it,
and the more souls that are

01:06:55.702 --> 01:06:59.722
enamored there above the more
there are to be rightly loved

01:06:59.722 --> 01:07:04.021
and the more love there is and
like a mirror the one returns it

01:07:04.021 --> 01:07:05.268
to the other.
 

01:07:05.268 --> 01:07:09.414
And if my speech do not relieve
thy hunger thou shalt see

01:07:09.414 --> 01:07:13.856
Beatrice and she will deliver
thee wholly from this and every

01:07:13.856 --> 01:07:15.190
other craving.
 

01:07:15.190 --> 01:07:19.797
Strive only that soon may be
erased, as the other two are

01:07:19.797 --> 01:07:23.829
already, the five wounds which
are healed by being

01:07:23.829 --> 01:07:25.309
painful."
 

01:07:25.309 --> 01:07:29.112
The question is,
you want me to say something

01:07:29.112 --> 01:07:33.260
about the mirror,
the image of the mirror that is

01:07:33.260 --> 01:07:34.989
being used here.
 

01:07:34.989 --> 01:07:42.945
I think that this is a Platonic
image of the notion that all of

01:07:42.945 --> 01:07:49.875
creation--this is The
Celestial Hierarchy of the

01:07:49.875 --> 01:07:52.570
Pseudo-Dionysius.
 

01:07:52.570 --> 01:07:55.099
I don't know that I have ever
spoken of him,

01:07:55.099 --> 01:07:58.300
I will because Dante mentions
him in Paradise,

01:07:58.300 --> 01:08:00.070
but in The Celestial
Hierarchy,

01:08:00.070 --> 01:08:03.896
Dante--the
Pseudo-Dionysius--thinks of all

01:08:03.896 --> 01:08:07.349
creation being a kind of
occasion--

01:08:07.349 --> 01:08:14.603
being a kind of hall of mirrors
where everything is reflected

01:08:14.603 --> 01:08:20.786
onto the other,
a number of reflections that

01:08:20.786 --> 01:08:26.323
all give different light--
in different ways the light of

01:08:26.323 --> 01:08:29.322
God,
this is so--that's where the

01:08:29.322 --> 01:08:33.529
problem of mercy places us,
so this idea of charity.

01:08:33.529 --> 01:08:38.064
Dante is interested in two
things, one the generative idea

01:08:38.064 --> 01:08:39.100
of charity.
 

01:08:39.100 --> 01:08:42.368
Charity produces more charity.
 

01:08:42.368 --> 01:08:47.720
It has a kind of power to
generate itself and multiply

01:08:47.720 --> 01:08:51.180
itself,
and the way he compares this

01:08:51.180 --> 01:08:54.328
is--he compares it to what I
call--

01:08:54.328 --> 01:08:57.180
what he calls here,
obliquely, the hall of mirrors.

01:08:57.180 --> 01:09:02.220
Let me just say something else
about Pseudo-Dionysius,

01:09:02.220 --> 01:09:06.988
when Pseudo-Dionysius wants
to--mystical theology--

01:09:06.988 --> 01:09:11.938
he wants to talk about the
divine, he will think about the

01:09:11.938 --> 01:09:15.328
divine in terms of light,
as you know.

01:09:15.328 --> 01:09:20.640
Light that is refracted and
reflected throughout the orders

01:09:20.640 --> 01:09:22.840
and ranks of creation.
 

01:09:22.840 --> 01:09:29.720
The highest image of this light
of the divine is the sun.

01:09:29.720 --> 01:09:33.788
The sun that is generous,
in the sense,

01:09:33.788 --> 01:09:35.640
as I mean generous in a very
peculiar sense,

01:09:35.640 --> 01:09:39.310
in the sense that it gives
itself to all,

01:09:39.310 --> 01:09:43.760
without any distinction and it
depends on us,

01:09:43.760 --> 01:09:47.569
whether we are going to be able
to appreciate that light or not,

01:09:47.569 --> 01:09:51.760
but the sun is giving itself
freely to all.

01:09:51.760 --> 01:09:54.600
This is the principle of mercy
for Dante.

01:09:54.600 --> 01:09:58.868
Mirrors are reproducing that
light endlessly;

01:09:58.868 --> 01:10:02.851
the whole of creation is
sending back this kind of light,

01:10:02.851 --> 01:10:06.479
without any loss in itself of
the original light.

01:10:06.479 --> 01:10:11.158
This is the metaphor and the
metaphysics of mirror in Dante.

01:10:11.158 --> 01:10:14.487
The world is therefore,
from the point of view of

01:10:14.487 --> 01:10:17.605
mercy, and not from the point of
view of envy,

01:10:17.605 --> 01:10:20.310
where we do not even see the
light.

01:10:20.310 --> 01:10:24.592
Envy means that we have no
knowledge of anything that comes

01:10:24.592 --> 01:10:29.288
from the outside,
but in the world of mercy we

01:10:29.288 --> 01:10:32.863
have an--
we understand this generous

01:10:32.863 --> 01:10:38.431
giving of the light which comes
from God and the heat that goes

01:10:38.431 --> 01:10:39.420
with it.
 

01:10:39.420 --> 01:10:46.663
That's it, so it's a virtue
that completely offsets the

01:10:46.663 --> 01:10:51.201
notion of envy,
the idea of God who creates

01:10:51.201 --> 01:10:54.505
without envy,
that's another way of thinking

01:10:54.505 --> 01:10:56.560
about the generosity of God.
 

01:10:56.560 --> 01:11:00.528
That is connected to the light
and to the multiplications of

01:11:00.528 --> 01:11:02.210
the light from mirrors.
 

01:11:02.210 --> 01:11:07.988
Actually this is an image that
really reappears in

01:11:07.988 --> 01:11:14.238
Paradise and we'll come
back to this canto,

01:11:14.238 --> 01:11:19.850
the whole of Paradise organized
through this hall,

01:11:19.850 --> 01:11:32.529
these infinite reflections of
God's light.

